The results of this work show that two types of microstructures which are kinetically stable at room temperature can be produced in the HfNbTaTiZr alloy. The first comprises a single-phase BCC crystal structure formed during annealing above ~1000 °C, which does not undergo a phase transformation during slow cooling after annealing. This single-phase structure is retained even after severe room-temperature deformation. The second type of microstructure consists of a BCC1 matrix rich in Hf and Zr with globular, submicron-size BCC2 precipitates rich in Nb and Ta, which are present after annealing at 800 °C. Both microstructures have high tensile strength, reasonable ductility, and ductile type of fracture.

A single-phase BCC NbTaHfTiZr refractory high entropy alloy was cold worked to a total reduction of 89 pct (effective true strain = 2.55) using upset forging (54.5 pct thickness reduction, true strain = À 0.91) followed by rolling (75.8 pct thickness reduction, true strain = À 1.64). The cold-worked alloy retained its single-phase structure and had room temperature yield stress r 0.2 = 1438 MPa, peak stress r p = 1495 MPa, and fracture strain e f = 5 pct.
